Abstract

The following are notes, graphs and R scripts inspired by the article Bootstrap Your Standard Errors in R, the Tidy Way by Steve Miller.

library(knitr)
library(kableExtra)
library(data.table)
library(modelr)
library(here)
library(RregressPkg)
library(RplotterPkg)
library(ggplot2)

current_dir <- here()

Homoskedasticity a definition

Steve Millers definition:

the variability of our variable (response) is unequal across the range of our variables (predictors) that we believe explain it.

The condition is often referred to as heteroskedasticity.

From Wikipedia:
A standard assumption in a linear regression, \(y_{i} = X_{i} \beta + \epsilon_{i} , i = 1 , , N\) , is that the variance of the disturbance term \(\epsilon_{i}\) is the same across observations, and in particular does not depend on the values of the explanatory variables \(X_{i}\).

Mr.Miller hints at how we might detect the presence of a non-random pattern in the disturbance term by looking at the plot between the fitted value and the prediction error thats dependent on the predictor variables.

Mr.Miller also states that homoskedasticity is one of the most important assumptions of an OLS model thats easy to violate. In addition, violating this assumption of homoskedasticity mostly concern our standard errors around our coefficients.

Heteroskedasticity a solution

Mr.Miller suggests a technique called bootstrapping which he illustrates with an example data set.

His goal in the article:

Here, Ill hope to make it more transparent and explain whats happening in bootstrapping standard errors that both shows how to do it and explains what bootstrapping is doing.

Crime data set

Mr.Miller describes the data as statewide crime data from around 1993 that includes 51 observations (i.e.50 states + DC).

The response and predictor variables are as follows:
Crime Data Set
Variable Description
state char - state
violent numeric - violent rate per 100000
murder numeric - murder rate per 100000
poverty numeric - percent below poverty level
single numeric - percent families headed by single parent
metro numeric - percent of pop in metro areas
white numeric - percent of state is white
highschool numeric - percent of state grad from hs

OLS preliminaries

Mr.Miller proposes to set up an OLS model with violent as the response and poverty, single, metro, white, highschool as predictors.

To get more familiar with the data I propose that we complete two plots:

  1. A matrix of scatter plots that show pattens among the variables of interest.

  2. A plot of the 51 observations with their respective violent values to check for any potential outliers or observations that have undue influence on the OLS.

The matrix of scatter plots:

crime_ols <- RregressPkg::ols_calc(

OLS assumption of homoskedasticity

We want to test if the expected squares of the residuals (\(\hat{\mu_{i}}^2\)) in the original model are related to one or more of the predictor variables. By related we could investigate if there is a linear relationship between an original models residuals and its predictors. The linear equation involving the residuals with the predictor variables could be defined as:

\[\hat{\mu}^2 = \delta_{0} + \delta_{1}x_{1} + \delta_{2}x_{2} + ... + \delta_{k}x_{k} + error\]

Our null hypothesis is that there is no relationship between residuals and predictors, i.e.

\[H_{0}: \delta_{0} = \delta_{1} = ... = \delta_{k} = 0\]

In testing this hypothesis, we could set up a full and restricted model for an \(F\)-Test or a restricted model for an \(LM\)-test (Lagrange multiplier statistic).

Well follow Mr.Millers lead and do both a test and a plot:

  1. Compute the Breusch-Pagan test for heteroskedasticity.

  2. A plot of the observations OLS fitted values with their residual values.

Performing the BP-test:

bp_test_df <- RregressPkg::ols_BP_test_calc(
  df = crime_dt,
  formula_obj = ViolentC ~ Poverty + Single + Metro + White + HSGrad
)

RplotterPkg::create_table(
  x = bp_test_df,
  caption = "A Breusch-Pagan test for Heteroskedasticity",
  head_bkgd = "purple",
  head_col = "white"
)
A Breusch-Pagan test for Heteroskedasticity
F_Val F_p LM_Val LM_p
3.892318 0.0051278 15.3974 0.0087926
Take Away: With \(p\)-values on the border of accepting the \(H_{0}\) we will conclude based on the test that their is some relationship between residuals and predictors.


The plot of fitted values versus residuals:

residuals_df <- data.frame(
  Fitted = crime_ols$fitted_val,
  Residuals = crime_ols$resid,
  State = crime_dt$State
)
RplotterPkg::create_scatter_plot(
  df = residuals_df,
  aes_x = "Fitted",
  aes_y = "Residuals",
  aes_label = "State",
  title = "Fitted versus Residuals",
  subtitle = "ViolentC ~ Poverty + Single + Metro + White + HSGrad",
  rot_y_tic_label = T,

)

Bootstrapping

Continuing along, lets bootstrap the data set for 1000 resamples.

  1. Set the seed and call modelr::bootstrap() to create 1000 sets of predictor values:
set.seed(8675309)
boot_df <- modelr::bootstrap(crime_dt, 1000)
boot_dt <- data.table::setDT(boot_df)
  1. For each 1000 sets of predictor values, from a vectorized function compute the OLS estimate and return the models coefficients as a list. Convert the list of lists of coefficients into a data.table using data.table::rbindlist():
make_cof <- function(x){
  model_x <- lm(
    formula = ViolentC ~ Poverty + Single + Metro + White + HSGrad,
    data = x)
  as.list(model_x$coefficients)
}

beta_lst <- lapply(boot_dt$strap, make_cof)
beta_dt <- data.table::rbindlist(beta_lst)

We now have 1000 estimates of each of the coefficients.

  1. Create a bootstrap related data table of stats containing (with the exception of (Intercept)) coefficient names and their values from the original OLS:
boot_stats_dt <- data.table(
  Source = "Boot",
  Predictor = crime_ols$coef_df$Coef,
  Beta = crime_ols$coef_df$Value
)
boot_stats_dt <- boot_stats_dt[Predictor != "(Intercept)"]
  1. From the 1000 estimates of each coefficient in beta_dt compute the standard deviation (the coefficients standard error). Add the standard errors for each coefficient as a column to boot_stats_dt:
boot_stats_dt[, se := unlist(lapply(boot_stats_dt$Predictor, function(x) sd(beta_dt[[x]])))]
  1. Using the se values, add columns for the lower and upper confidence limits for the coefficients to boot_stats_dt;
boot_stats_dt[, `:=`(
  lwr = Beta - 1.645*se,
  upr = Beta + 1.645*se
)]
  1. Create a normal related data table with stats from the original OLS coefficient values with their standard errors, lower and upper confidence limits.
coef_dt <- data.table::setDT(crime_ols$coef_df)
coef_dt <- coef_dt[Coef != "(Intercept)"]
normal_stats_dt <- data.table(
  Source = "Normal",
  Predictor = coef_dt$Coef,
  Beta = coef_dt$Value,
  se = coef_dt$SE,
  lwr = coef_dt$Value - 1.625*coef_dt$SE,
  upr = coef_dt$Value + 1.625*coef_dt$S
)

7.Row bind the bootstrap and normal stats data tables and plot:

stats_dt <- rbind(boot_stats_dt, normal_stats_dt)
stats_dt[, `:=`(Predictor = as.factor(Predictor), Source = as.factor(Source))]

RplotterPkg::multi_scatter_plot(
  df = stats_dt,
  factor_var = "Predictor",
  factor_x = "Beta",
  columns = 3,
  aes_y = "Source",
  title = "A Comparison of Normal OLS and Bootstrapped Coefficient Standard Errors",
  rot_y_tic_label = T,
  CI_lwr = "lwr",
  CI_upr = "upr",
  CI_dir = "x",
  CI_size = 0.8,
  CI_color = "red",
  pts_size = 3.5,
  pts_color = "blue",
  pts_fill = "blue"
)

Take Away: As noted by Mr.Miller:


The ensuing plot suggests the standard errors most influenced by the heteroskedasicity in our model are those for the single family home variable and especially the percentage of the state that is white variable.
